post_text:
FOOTBALL RESUMES: Charles City High School Football is resuming practice on Monday, September 14.

In order to be cleared for school on Monday, any student who tested positive for COVID 19 will have to complete their quarantined AND be 24 hours with no fever (without the use of fever-reducing medicine) AND symptoms are improving AND 10 days since symptoms started; if no symptoms, 10 days from the day of the test.

All Charles City High School athletes are required to perform an online daily COVID check prior to participating in practice. Players must pass the COVID check two consecutive days before a practice. All football players will need to pass checks on Varsity Bound Sunday and Monday in order to participate on Monday.

The weight room for all sports is closed until further notice. The Thursday, September 17, 9th grade football game is canceled.

Charles City High School football plays at Manchester vs. the West Delaware Hawks on Friday, September 18.

post_text: GAITERS: Uniforms for Charles City Community Schools athletes are getting a COVID-19 update this fall. The activity office will provide orange neck gaiters for use during games and practices. The expectation for students is when they are actively participating in athletics face coverings are not required. The new uniform element will provide students the opportunity to cover quickly during downtime. The gaiters will provide access to protection when students are on the sidelines, in huddles, timeouts, and before and after game time.

post_text:
Cleaning protocols
We continue to implement high-quality cleaning procedures at all of our campuses in preparation for students to return to school. Here are some highlights of what we are doing to keep our school family safe.

Our custodial staff at each campus are using a hospital-grade disinfectant cleaner, it is effective against a broad spectrum of bacteria, and can destroy viruses

-Hand sanitizer stations are located in each building
-Hand sanitizer and sanitizer wipes are in each classroom for student and staff use
-A spray bottle of hospital grade disinfectant is located in each classroom
-All common areas will be disinfected by custodial staff on an hourly basis and each night
-Playground equipment will be disinfected regularly
-Buses will be disinfected after every route by our professional drivers

FOOD SERVICE CHANGE: We’re making some changes to food service beginning in June.

June and July food service will be distributed once a week (10 meals per student) on Thursdays. The location will change to the high school. Satellite deliveries will continue in normal locations. We are extending summer food service until July 31, 2020.

Next week's food pick-up will be on May 26 and 28 and will be at Washington Elementary School and satellite locations. Sign up at this link for next week’s food service

Are you ready for the next challenge, Charles City Comets? Create a beautiful easter egg on a piece of paper (sized 4" X 6", 5" X 7", OR 8" X 10") and cut them out for us. Deliver to a staff member in the lunch pick up line at Washington Elementary School any time between 11:00 - 12:30 on Wednesday, Thursday or Friday of this week. We will then take all of the eggs and decorate the outdoor areas of our local nursing homes. Ready. Set. Go. We miss you! Tag and Share with friends and family! #CharlesCityExperience

post_text:
Q. What’s happening with tonight’s school board meeting?

A. The next school board meeting is tonight, Monday, March 23 at 6:15 p.m. The board of education will meet via a Google Hangout. On the agenda, published on our website on Friday, there will be a call-in number to listen to the meeting and we will also be streaming the meeting via Facebook LIVE. The meeting is open to the public to watch, anyone who would like to participate during the public comment section should call into the phone number provided on the agenda. You may call-in and live stream with us. The Governor made a change to the meeting requirements on Friday, in the interest of public health and social distance protocols. The meeting will be completely online. This is a short term solution to our open meeting requirements during the COVID-19 outbreak. Even with the changes, we are exceeding the minimum requirements required by state guidelines with the Facebook Live broadcast. https://www.charlescityschools.org/board

post_text:
UPDATES: Charles City Community Schools will continue with daily updates to the community for as long as we have news to share. Look for these updates through text and email each day around 6 p.m. If you are not getting these messages and would like to receive them, please visit our website and sign up for Community-Wide Notifications.

Also Sunday night Charles City Community Schools were leaders in the state by extending our spring break by six days. Within hours of our decision, the Governor closed schools statewide for four weeks. We will comply with the Governor’s decision and at this time we are planning to see students again on April 13.

Watch for more updates late today. #CharlesCityExperience

post_text:
COVID-19: In Charles City Community Schools the health, safety, and well-being of our Family (students and staff) are our top priorities. With the recently elevated discussion regarding COVID-19, we want to answer some possible questions you might have as we return from spring break.

Accurate information is more important than ever. We pledge to share updates with you as quickly as possible, with full transparency and, as always, with community safety foremost in mind.

As a school district, we are closely monitoring the situation and taking guidance from the Iowa Department of Public Health. We are in daily communication with Floyd County Public Health.

If you have any questions after reading the FAQ please let us know. We have a link to ask questions at the end of the FAQ where we will answer questions individually or we will include them in future FAQs.

Please take a moment to review this Family FAQ for more information. http://bit.ly/3cXbCyx

SPOTLIGHT: Students from Charles City's CNA program have journalists from Iowa Ideas shadowing them this morning. The students, who are studying and performing their clinicals to receive their CNA license are being profiled today for the annual publication.

These CNA students arrive at Chautauqua Guest Homes at 5:40 a.m. each morning and then put in a full day of school after their morning class.

Iowa Ideas tells stories of key questions and big ideas that will shape the state's future. #CharlesCityExperience

post_text: IN THE CLASSROOM: 4th grade students are reading a historical fiction book, “Pink and Say” about two soldiers in the Civil War. Conversations in the class help students decipher what is history and what is fiction. This also introduces new words like inconsolable, ransacked, cleaved, smote, and marauders, to the 4th graders vocabulary. Themes in the book center around service, racism, war, and friendship. #CharlesCityExperience

post_text: CANCELED CAFÉ: The Comet Café originally scheduled for Thursday, January 30, is canceled. The FCS program is housed in the 600 circle of the high school which is currently facing on-going problems with its plumbing infrastructure, which is forcing the change. The plumbing in the 1963 classroom of the Charles City High School was not built to handle a career readiness program such as pro-start (the parent class of Comet Café). Even though the school district has made improvements to the classroom, instruction, equipment, technology, and modernized the curriculum, the underground plumbing of the building is not built to handle the demands. Because of this situation, the FCS classroom’s kitchen is temporarily being vacated and moved to the middle school FCS classroom until the plumbing infrastructure is repaired and the area is appropriately sanitized to meet appropriate food and health codes.

CUDDLY HELP: 4th grade Charles City Lincoln Elementary students donated more than 30 blankets to be used in the community during emergency situations. The Charles City Police Department, Charles City Fire Rescue, and American Medical Response received the student made blankets so first responders will be able to comfort kids directly during a crisis.

Left over material not large enough for a full size blanket was assembled for animals at PAWS Humane Society.

Thanks to the employees of JOANN Fabric and Craft Stores for contributing material for this #CharlesCityExperience project.

Special thanks to the employees of JOANN Fabric and Craft Stores. When the store manager was approached about a possible fabric donation, store employees personally took up a collection and donated their personal fabric.

The #CharlesCityExperience goes well beyond our school walls, and student leadership is benefiting the entire community.

post_text: EXPERIENCE: Welcome to Charles City Community Schools, where we are family, and we do what is best for all kids. Here’s a glimpse inside our schools and the #CharlesCityExperience.
text: EXPERIENCE: Welcome to Charles City Community Schools, where we are family, and we do what is best for all kids. Here’s a glimpse inside our schools and the #CharlesCityExperience.

post_text: FAMILY: Our elementary school students are ready for Thanksgiving around your table. Today our students ate a Thanksgiving meal family-style. They had lessons in etiquette, manners, and patience. They learned how to be independent, proper proportion sizes, and they even tried new food. Our students naturally took to serving others and lived up to their core values. This is just another example of the #CharlesCityExperience. We appreciate the parent volunteers who helped serve today.

With one phone call at 9:30 p.m. Saturday night, these businesses are making sure our guests this afternoon have programs. The programs are printed locally at the Charles City Press and First Security Bank & Trust sponsors the printing of the program.

The last performance is today. Support our students and see the show everyone is talking about.

post_text:
TICKET PUNCHED: For the fourth consecutive year, the Charles City Girls Cross Country team is headed to state! Charles City finished 3rd at the state qualifying meet in Independence last week qualifying the team for state.

Charles City also has 3 individual state qualifiers who placed in the top 15. Kiki Connell was the state qualifying meet champion finishing in 19:01. Lydia Staudt finished in 9th place with a career-best time of 20:08. Mackenzy Bilharz was 13th in the 2nd fastest time of her career (20:20).
